<font color="#FF0000">CLARIFICATION</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan  7 13:15:25 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
To clarify some of the points I made, I add a few thoughts.<br><br>
First, banned books tend to sell better in the United States than uncontroversial ones.  Therefore, to keep a book out of the hands of Americans, other measures are necessary.  For one thing, if the Black Book of Communism is not translated from French into English or not distributed by one of the large publishing houses, most Americans will never know that the book even exists.  The publishing houses with distribution networks capable of making books best sellers are in the hands of only a few people, and they are responsible for controlling what information most Americans receive.<br><br>
Second, the excesses of President Diem against the communists opens a very broad question of how far a government may go to defend itself against attack.  Usually, excesses occur when a government is confronted by terrorist methods, because these methods are deliberately chosen to provoke overreaction, causing the leaders to discredit themselves.  The communists Diem was dealing were being sent to North Vietnam for training in guerilla warfare and terrorist methods and returning to put what they had learned into practice. They were systematically assassinating all persons who worked in any capacity with the government together with their wives and children.  The victims were not only village chiefs and military personnel but also teachers and public health officials, including the people working to control malaria under a U.N. program.  Diem´s anti-communist campaigns may have been excessive, but so were the methods of McCarthy´s committee in the United States, which existed during the same years. Americans who were not communists were blacklisted without giving them a fair chance to defend themselves.  The point is that any government may overreact when confronted with terrorism or other tactics of violence, while some governments do not act strongly enough, permitting their countries to be taken over by terrorists who rule through the muzzles of their guns.<br>
In July of 1863, the first draft lottery in the U. S. A. was instituted.  In New York City, protests were begun not only a large number of poor people but also by Horatio Seymour, the Governor of the state, who declared the law to be unconstitutional.  The protests turned into riots, which were directed against pro-draft politicians, the New York Herold, and any former slaves the mob could find.  Lincoln detached some of the troops that had just won the Battle of Gettysburg and sent them to New York, where they opened fire on the mob, killing over a hundred protesters.  All together, there were about 1000 casualties.  In fact, the draft was not at all fair because a person could get out of service after his number was called by paying a sum of money or by hiring a person to take his place.  Nevertheless, President Lincoln, protecting his elected government, did what he thought was necessary to restore order.<br>
The first freely elected government in Germany, called the Weimar Republic, was destroyed amid street battles between the communists and the brown shirts.  These two extremist groups fought each other but both agreed that the republican form of government had to be eliminated.  Finally, the brown shirts won, and the world found itself on the road to World War II.  Would the elected officials of the Weimar Republic have been wrong to take more vigorous and effective action to keep both the communists and the nazis from destroying it and replacing it with a totalitarian state?<br>
I am not trying to endorse or condemn any of the people responsible for these historical events.  It should be evident that any democratic government or any government of another form is sometimes faced with violent opposition, and it is not always an easy matter to decide how far to go in eliminating opposition parties that resort to assassination and terrorism to obtain power.<br><br>
Third, I referred to the right to protest both in the United States and in South Vietnam, at least during the years after Diem´s murder.  I have no personal knowledge of what went on in Vietnam while Diem was president and I hesitate to accept either American or communist accounts of what he was doing.  After all, he opposed the communists actively and was murdered at least with the passive assent of the Kennedy Administration.  Hence, both parties have reason to paint him as a villain.  Speaking for the right to protest while Diem was still alive is the fact that pictures of burning monks appeared on the cover of American magazines that were circulated in South Vietnam at the time.  I cannot imagine that a monk who burned himself in Hanoi would have appeared in any magazine.  Furthermore, I cannot imagine that a monk would have had the chance to do so in North Vietnam.  Generally, in communist countries, the Buddhist monks were imprisoned.  I personally knew someone who spent three years in a Chinese prison during the 1950s, where the communists were holding the equivalent of the Buddhist Pope together with several other leading monks.<br>
In any case, I personally witnessed a large South Vietnamese protest march, which was by no means pro-communist. However, it was rabidly anti-government and attacked corruption and the draft.  This march through Saigon was completed without incident.<br><br>

